Creating a simple Windows 95 clone in a single HTML file with embedded CSS and JavaScript can be a fun project. Below is a basic example that mimics the look and feel of Windows 95. This example includes a desktop area, a taskbar, and a simple start menu.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Windows 95 Clone</title>
    <style>
        body {
            background-color: #008080;
            font-family: 'MS Sans Serif', Tahoma, Geneva, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            overflow: hidden;
        }
        #taskbar {
            background-color: #C0C0C0;
            height: 40px;
            position: absolute;
            bottom: 0;
            width: 100%;
            border-top: 2px solid #FFFFFF;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            padding-left: 10px;
        }
        #start-button {
            background-color: #C0C0C0;
            border: 2px outset #FFFFFF;
            padding: 5px 10px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        #desktop {
            position: absolute;
            top: 0;
            bottom: 40px;
            left: 0;
            right: 0;
            overflow: hidden;
        }
        .icon {
            width: 64px;
            height: 64px;
            text-align: center;
            margin: 10px;
            display: inline-block;
            cursor: pointer;
            position: relative;
        }
        .icon img {
            width: 48px;
            height: 48px;
        }
        .start-menu {
            display: none;
            position: absolute;
            bottom: 40px;
            left: 0;
            background-color: #C0C0C0;
            border: 2px outset #FFFFFF;
            padding: 10px;
            width: 150px;
            z-index: 1000;
        }
        .start-menu div {
            padding: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .start-menu div:hover {
            background-color: #A0A0A0;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="desktop">
        <div class="icon" onclick="alert('My Computer opened!')">
            <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/48?text=PC" alt="My Computer">
            <div>My Computer</div>
        </div>
        <div class="icon" onclick="alert('Recycle Bin opened!')">
            <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/48?text=RB" alt="Recycle Bin">
            <div>Recycle Bin</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div id="taskbar">
        <div id="start-button" onclick="toggleStartMenu()">Start</div>
    </div>
    <div class="start-menu" id="start-menu">
        <div onclick="alert('Programs clicked!')">Programs</div>
        <div onclick="alert('Documents clicked!')">Documents</div>
        <div onclick="alert('Settings clicked!')">Settings</div>
        <div onclick="alert('Shut Down clicked!')">Shut Down</div>
    </div>

    <script>
        function toggleStartMenu() {
            const menu = document.getElementById('start-menu');
            menu.style.display = menu.style.display === 'block' ? 'none' : 'block';
        }

        window.onclick = function(event) {
            if (!event.target.matches('#start-button')) {
                const menu = document.getElementById('start-menu');
                if (menu.style.display === 'block') {
                    menu.style.display = 'none';
                }
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The HTML consists of a desktop area, a taskbar, and a start menu.
- **CSS Styles**: The CSS styles mimic the Windows 95 look with a teal background, gray taskbar, and simple icons.
- **JavaScript Functionality**: The JavaScript toggles the visibility of the start menu and handles clicks outside the menu to close it.

### Usage:
1. Copy the code above into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `windows95_clone.html`).
3. Open the file in a web browser to see the Windows 95 clone in action.

Feel free to expand upon this basic structure by adding more icons, functionality, or styles!
